{
    "analysis": "We aggregated metrics, traces, and logs and computed global thresholds (P95) on full series before filtering to the incident window. Metric-level anomalies identified JVM-heap and host/CPU/request KPIs on IG02, MG02, MG01, Tomcat02/03/04. Trace analysis shows a short, simultaneous surge in row_count originating at IG02 toward Tomcat02/03/04 and MG01 at ~18:00–18:03, with MG02 exhibiting concurrent latency (duration_p95/duration_mean) spikes. Log analysis showed Tomcat02/03/04 row_count spikes and isolated GC pause breaches slightly later (~18:06–18:17). Error logs contained no explicit exceptions for these components in-window.\n\nKey chronological evidence: the earliest breach across candidate components is IG02 (trace.to_Tomcat03.row_count) at 2021-03-23 18:00:00+08:00. Multiple downstream components show faults immediately afterwards (Tomcat row_count spikes at ~18:01–18:03 and MG02 latency at ~18:00–18:03). No error-log messages contradict this causal ordering.\n\nApplying the fault-localization rules: the root cause occurrence is the first data point of the initiating fault. Although downstream services (Tomcats, MG02) were also faulty, the initiating faulty component in the trace call chain is IG02. The anomalies are brief (few data points) and consist of large row_count/traffic spikes that temporally precede downstream CPU/GC/latency signs. Therefore IG02 is the most plausible single root cause component, with the incident originating at the first anomalous trace point.",
